d in the third about the contributions of the public sector. Through these movements, Jane L. Collins maps a set of cultural conversations about the types of investments and activities that contribute to the health of the economy. Compelling and persuasive, The Politics of Value offers a new framework for viewing economic value, one grounded in thoughtful assessment of the social division of labor and the relationship of the state and the market to civil society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aCommon goodxEconomic aspects. 0aEconomicsxPolitical aspects. 0aEconomicsxSociological aspects. 0aSocial movementszUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aSocial responsibility of business. 0aValuexSocial aspects. 0aValue. 4aGreat Recession. 4aSlow Money. 4aWisconsin Uprising. 4aausterity politics. 4abenefit corporations. 4acorporate governance. 4aeconomic value. 4apublic sector. 4ashareholder value. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226446288423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226446288.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles